benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: GET /1.0/kb/catalog/versions - Retrieve a list of catalog versions

covered: Valid Request: Multiple successful retrieval scenarios (global and tenant/account-specific) are covered (TC01, TC02).
Empty Response: Explicit scenarios for no catalog versions and regression checks ensure empty-array handling (TC03, TC13).

Query Parameters: Tests for valid accountId, non-existent accountId, invalid formats, empty, leading/trailing spaces, mixed case, unsupported parameters, and SQL-injection attempts (TC02, TC04, TC05, TC09, TC12, TC16, TC17, TC18).
Authorization: Authentication missing and invalid/expired token scenarios are present (TC06, TC07).
Error Handling: Service unavailable and malformed JSON/server error cases are included (TC08, TC19), plus timeout downstream behavior (TC11).
Performance/Load: Large dataset and concurrency performance tests are included (TC10, TC15).
Content Type / Machine-readable: Content-type and machine-readable response checks are present (TC01, TC20).
gaps: Pagination: No tests for pagination, limits, offsets, or behavior when result sets are large beyond a single full response (no page/limit/next link checks).
Caching Behavior: No scenarios validating caching headers (ETag, Last-Modified, Cache-Control) or conditional GET behavior (304 Not Modified).

Rate Limiting/Throttling: No specific tests for rate limiting responses (e.g., 429 Too Many Requests) or throttling behavior under burst traffic; concurrency tests exist but do not assert rate-limit semantics.
Authorization nuances: No tests for forbidden access (403) vs unauthenticated (401) — e.g., authenticated user without tenant access, or cross-tenant access restrictions.
Response Schema / Data Quality: No tests verifying ordering, uniqueness, duplicate effective dates, or date normalization (timezones), nor maximum/minimum date bounds and sorting semantics.
Content Negotiation: No tests for Accept headers other than application/json or for graceful rejection when unsupported media types are requested.
Pagination-related performance: While large dataset is tested, there is no test for streaming/partial responses or memory/heap impact on server for huge responses beyond timing.
recommendations: Add pagination tests: include page/limit params (if supported) or test that API either rejects or handles pagination-related queries; verify behavior for very large result sets with and without pagination, presence of paging headers (Link, next, prev).
Add caching tests: assert presence and correctness of Cache-Control, ETag, Last-Modified headers; test conditional GET (If-None-Match / If-Modified-Since) and expected 304 responses.
Add rate-limiting tests: simulate bursts to verify 429 responses and Retry-After header behavior, and validate system behavior under throttling.
Add authorization edge cases: test authenticated users lacking tenant access (expect 403), and cross-tenant access restrictions; verify token scopes/roles if applicable.

Harden response validations: add tests for ordering, duplicates, timezone normalization, maximum length, and invalid date strings in persisted data; verify no PII or sensitive data leaks in error responses.
Add content negotiation tests: send Accept: text/html or */* and assert proper handling/406 or default JSON response.

Augment performance tests: monitor memory and resource utilization for very large responses and verify streaming or chunked responses where applicable; include SLA assertions beyond response time (CPU, memory thresholds).
